      <div class="jumbotron">
        <h1 class="text-center">Benjamin Banneker</h1>
      <h2 class="text-center">Creater of the Almanac and Clock</h2>
        <div class="thumbnail"><img src="http://www.famous-black-inventors.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Benjamin-Banneker.jpg" alt="">
          <h2 class="text-center"><em>Timeline of Benjamin Banneker's life</em></h2>
         <ul>
          <li>November 9, 1731 - Born in Baltimore County, Maryland</li>
          <li>1753 - Banneker constructs a clock using mostly wood based on his designs and calculations</li>
          <li>1771 - Banneker befriends the Ellicot brothers who encourage him to learn astronomy and mathematics by loaning him their books. He uses this to teach himself astronomy and advanced mathematics </li>
          <li>1775 - Banneker inherits the family farm which he constructs a skylight to study the stars and a make calculations</li>
          <li>1788 - Predicts a solar eclipse by using the tools and books loaned to him by the Ellicot brothers which was a nearly accurate but not due to his error but to a discrepancy in his expert sources</li>
          <li>February 1791 - Becomes an assistant in the survey of the District of Columbia. He is hired by Major Andrew Ellicot, cousin of the Ellicot brothers. He was able to recreate the plans from memory saving the US goverment a lot of time and money</li>
          <li>April 1791 - Banneker leaves the survey postion due to illness and difficulties completing the survey</li>
          <li>1792 - Publishes the first of his almanacs which are based on his ephemeris. The almanacs also include literature, commentaries and fillers that have a humanitarian and political nature</li>
          <li>1793 - Banneker's almanacs includes letters from Thomas Jefferson who critized Jeffersons proslavery stance</li>
          <li>1793 - Banneker recieves support from abolitionist societies in Maryland and Pennsylvania for his outspoken views on slavery, helping him publish his almanacs</li>
          <li>1797 - Banneker's last almanac is published due to declining sales</li>
           <li>1797 - Sells off part of the family farm in Maryland and gives the rest to the Ellicot brothers in exchange for a small pension</li>
           <li>October 9, 1806 - Banneker dies in his small cabin in Baltimore, Maryland. He never married or had any children. He was buried at the family burial grounds near the home</li>
           <li>1977 - A commemorative obelisk is erected</li>
          </ul>
           <blockquote>
           <h5>"The colour of the skin is in no way connected with the strength of the mind or intellectual powers."</h5>
             <footer><cite>- Benjamin Banneker</cite></footer>
           </blockquote>
          <h3>If you have time, you should read more about this incredible human being on his <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Banneker">Wikipedia entry</a>.</h3> 
